        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(whatsapp): support monitor socket substitution",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nPR #95920 was too broad to review because WhatsApp's socket seam was mixed with Crabline dependency and QA Lab transport wiring.\n\nThis PR isolates the WhatsApp foundation on top of the Slack foundation in #97154: the WhatsApp monitor can use an alternate Baileys-shaped socket factory without knowing about Crabline.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nOpenClaw's WhatsApp runtime opens Baileys sockets directly today. A realistic fake provider needs to plug in a Baileys-shaped socket implementation while the WhatsApp plugin continues to behave like it is talking to a normal WhatsApp socket.\n\nThis adds a typed socket factory seam to the connection controller, threads it through the monitor path, and exposes the monitor runtime option from the existing runtime-setter sidecar rather than broadening the public WhatsApp API barrel.\n\n## User Impact\n\nNormal WhatsApp users keep the real Baileys socket path. QA runtimes can substitute an equivalent socket factory before the WhatsApp monitor starts.\n\nStack:\n- Slack foundation: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/97154\n- WhatsApp foundation: this PR\n- QA Lab Crabline wiring: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/95920\n\n## Evidence\n\n- node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/whatsapp/src/connection-controller.test.ts src/plugins/contracts/plugin-sdk-runtime-api-guardrails.test.ts src/plugins/sdk-alias.test.ts\n- pnpm test:extensions:package-boundary:compile\n- pnpm tsgo:extensions\n- git diff --check\n",
